91 \n| ''[[Life Stinks]]''\n|\n| Stunt Coordinator - as David Richard Ellis\n|-\n| ''[[Wild Hearts Can't Be Broken]]''\n|\n| Stunt Coordinator\n|-\n| ''[[The Addams Family (1991 film)|The Addams Family]]''\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Stunt Coordinator - as David Ellis\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1992 \n| ''[[Kuffs]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Patriot Games (film)|Patriot Games]]''\n|\n| Stunt Coordinator\n|-\n| ''[[Forever Young (1992 film)|Forever Young]]''\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Stunt Coordinator - as David Ellis\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1993 \n| ''[[Body of Evidence (1993 film)|Body of Evidence]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sliver (film)|Sliver]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Made in America (1993 film)|Made in America]]''\n|\n| Stunt Coordinator\n|-\n| ''[[The Man Without a Face]]''\n|\n| Stunt Coordinator - as David Ellis\n|-\n| ''[[Warlock: The Armageddon]]''\n|\n| as David Ellis\n|-\n| 1994 \n| ''[[The Jungle Book (1994 film)|The Jungle Book]]''\n|\n| Stunt Coordinator: USA - as David Ellis\n|-\n| 1996 \n| ''[[Harriet the Spy (film)|Harriet the Spy]]''\n|\n| as Dave Ellis\n|-\n| 2009 \n| ''[[Hotel for Dogs (film)|Hotel for Dogs]]''\n|\n| as David Richard Ellis\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|0254786}}\n\n{{David R. Ellis}}\n{{Final Destination}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, David R.}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Film directors from California]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Horror film directors]]\n", "name_user": "DoubleCross", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:rm unlinked template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_R._Ellis"}
{"title_page": "Jorge Alfaro", "text_new": "{{short description|Colombian baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Spanish name 2|Alfaro|Buelvas}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name        = Jorge Alfaro\n|image       = Jorge Alfaro (46826926795) (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = Alfaro with the Marlins in 2019\n|image_size  = 240px\n|team        = Miami Marlins\n|number      = 38\n|position    = [[Catcher]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1993|6|11}}\n|birth_place = [[Sincelejo]], [[Colombia]]\n|bats        = Right\n|throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate   = September 12\n|debutyear   = 2016\n|debutteam   = Philadelphia Phillies\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|statleague  = MLB\n|stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value  = .266\n|stat3label  = [[Home run]]s\n|stat3value  = 33\n|stat4label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value  = 108\n|awards      = \n|teams       = \n*[[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|2016}}\u2013{{mlby|2018}})\n*[[Miami Marlins]] ({{mlby|2019}}\u2013present)\n}}\n'''Jorge Mario Alfaro Buelvas''' (born June 11, 1993) is a [[Colombians|Colombian]] [[professional baseball]] [[catcher]] for the [[Miami Marlins]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Alfaro signed with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] as a [[free agent]] in 2010, and was traded to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] in 2015. He made his MLB debut in 2016.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nAlfaro was born in [[Sincelejo]], [[Colombia]]. Alfaro's younger brother Jhoandro is a catcher in the [[Chicago White Sox]] organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/international/white-sox-sign-colombian-catcher-jhoandro-alfaro/|title=White Sox Sign Colombian Catcher Jhoandro Alfaro|first1=Ben|last1=Badler|date=July 2, 2014|website=baseballamerica.com|accessdate=June 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=alfaro000jho|title=Jhoandro Alfaro Minor Leagues Statistics & History|website=baseball-reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|access-date=August 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated6>[https://www.mlb.com/player/jorge-alfaro-595751 \"Jorge Alfaro Stats, Fantasy & News\" | MLB.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Alfaro played baseball and soccer at Instituto T\u00e9cnico Industrial Antonio Prieto, graduating in 2009.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==Career==\n===Texas Rangers organization===\nAlfaro signed with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in June 2010 as a 16-year-old [[free agent]] for a $1.3 million [[signing bonus]] that was a record at the time for any Colombian prospect.<ref>[https://thatballsouttahere.com/2016/02/10/phillies-top-10-prospects-6-jorge-alfaro/ \"Phillies Top 10 Prospects: #6 \u2013 Jorge Alfaro\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?sid=milb&player_id=595751#/career/R/hitting/2018/ALL \"Jorge Alfaro Stats, Highlights, Bio\" | MiLB.com Stats | The Official Site of Minor League Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated7>[https://www.lonestarball.com/2013/2/7/3961876/jorge-alfaro-scouting-report \"Jorge Alfaro Scouting Report\" - Lone Star Ball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2010, playing for the [[DSL Rangers]] in the [[Dominican Summer League]] he batted .221/.278/.291 with one [[home run]] and 23 [[RBI]]s.<ref name=autogenerated5>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=alfaro001jor \"Jorge Alfaro Minor, Winter & Fall Leagues Statistics & History\" | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn 2011, playing for the Class A Short-Season [[Spokane Indians]] in the [[Northwest League]], Alfaro batted .300/.345/.481 (9th in the league) with six home runs, 23 RBIs, and seven [[hit by pitch]] (6th) in 160 [[at bat]]s, as on defense he allowed 12 [[passed ball]]s and made 10 [[error]]s in 36 games at catcher.<ref name=autogenerated6 />  He was a ''[[Baseball America]]'' Short-Season All Star and a [[Topps]] Short-Season/Rookie All Star, and ''Baseball America'' named him the 8th-best prospect in the Northwest League.<ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=595751#/career/R/hitting/2018/ALL \"Jorge Alfaro Stats, Highlights, Bio\" | MiLB.com Stats | The Official Site of Minor League Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nIn 2012, playing for the Class A [[Hickory Crawdads]] in the [[South Atlantic League]], he batted .261/.320/.430 with five home runs and 34 RBIs in 272 at bats.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> ''Baseball America'' rated Alfaro the 9th-best Rangers prospect.<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\nPrior to the 2013 season Alfaro was ranked by [[MLB.com]] as the 88th-best prospect in baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130129&content_id=41240146&c_id=tex |first1=T.R. |last1=Sullivan |title=Rangers have six of game's Top 100 Prospects |publisher=MLB Advanced Media |website=rangers.mlb.com |date=January 29, 2013 |accessdate=December 14, 2013}}</ref> Alfaro was ranked the 54th-best prospect by ''Baseball America''. In 2013, playing for Hickory in the South Atlantic League, he was a mid-season All Star, an MiLB.com Texas Organization All Star, and an [[All-Star Futures Game]] selection.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> He batted .258/.338/.452 with 16 home runs, 53 RBIs, and 18 hit by pitch (leading the league) in 372 at bats, as on defense he allowed 26 passed balls and made 10 errors in 82 games at catcher.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> ''Baseball America'' named him the 14th-best prospect in the South Atlantic League.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> He also had 21 at bats with the [[AZL Rangers]], and 11 at bats with the [[Myrtle Beach Pelicans]].<ref name=autogenerated5 /> After the 2013 season he played for the [[Surprise Saguaros]] in the [[Arizona Fall League]], where he was batted .386 (3rd in the league)/.438 (9th)/.500 with 18 runs (5th), six [[double (baseball)|double]]s (6th), 11 RBIs, and three hit by pitch (2nd) in 70 at bats.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> He was named both a Rising Star and to the All-Prospect Team.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/11/texas-rangers-catching-prospect-shows-off-arm-in-afl.html/ |title=Texas Rangers catching prospect Jorge Alfaro shows off arm in AFL |publisher=Rangersblog.dallasnews.com |date=November 18, 2013 |accessdate=December 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214223048/http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/11/texas-rangers-catching-prospect-shows-off-arm-in-afl.html/ |archivedate=December 14, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/08/catcher-jorge-alfaro-heads-texas-rangers-list-of-prospects-in-arizona-fall-league.html/|title=Catcher Jorge Alfaro heads Texas Rangers list of prospects in Arizona Fall League|date=August 27, 2013|work=dallasnews.com|accessdate=June 28, 2016|first1=Evan|last1=Grant|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219021643/http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/08/catcher-jorge-alfaro-heads-texas-rangers-list-of-prospects-in-arizona-fall-league.html/|archive-date=February 19, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 playing for Class A-Advanced Myrtle Beach he was [[Carolina League]] Player of the Week on August 4, a mid-season All Star, an MiLB Texas Organization All Star, and a post-season All Star.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> Alfaro was also the starting catcher for the World Squad at the [[All-Star Futures Game]].<ref name=autogenerated6 />  For the season, he batted .261/.318/.440 with five triples (10th in the league), 13 home runs (6th), 73 RBIs (3rd), and 12 hit by pitch (4th), as on defense he allowed 18 passed balls and made 13 errors at catcher in 75 games.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> ''Baseball America'' named him the second-best prospect in the Carolina League.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> He also had 88 at bats with the Double-A [[Frisco RoughRiders]] of the [[Texas League]], batting .261/.343/.443 with four home runs and 14 RBIs.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\nOn November 20, 2014, the Rangers added Alfaro to their [[40-man roster]] to protect him from being selected in the [[Rule 5 draft]].<ref>[https://nolanwritin.com/2014/11/19/rule-5-draft-texas-rangers-must-finalize-40-man-roster-by-thursday-jorge-alfaro/ \"Rule-5 Draft: Texas Rangers must finalize 40-man roster by Thursday\"]</ref> In 2015 playing for Frisco he was a mid-season All Star, and batted .253/.314/.432 with five home runs and 21 RBIs in 190 at bats.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n===Philadelphia Phillies===\nOn July 31, 2015, the Rangers traded Alfaro, [[Nick Williams (baseball)|Nick Williams]], [[Matt Harrison (baseball)|Matt Harrison]], [[Jake Thompson]], [[Alec Asher]], and [[Jerad Eickhoff]] to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for [[Cole Hamels]] and [[Jake Diekman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/majors/trade-central-hamels-texas-ranger/|title=Trade Central: Phillies Get Impact Talent, Depth In Hamels Deal|first=Ben|last=Badler|website=baseballamerica.com|date=July 31, 2015|accessdate=July 31, 2015}}</ref> In the remainder of 2015 he had four at bats with the [[GCL Phillies]].<ref name=autogenerated5 /> ''Baseball America'' named him the 5th-best prospect in the Phillies minor league system.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nIn 2016 playing for the Double-A [[Reading Fightin Phils]] he was an [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] Player of the Week and Phillies Minor League Player of the Week on April 17, Phillies Minor League Defender of the Month for July, a mid-season All Star, and an MiLB Philadelphia Organization All Star.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref name=autogenerated6 />  The Phillies promoted Alfaro to the major leagues on August 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/197781550/phillies-call-no-4-prospect-jorge-alfaro/|title=Phillies call up No. 4 prospect Jorge Alfaro|first1=Joshua|last1=Needelman|website=mlb.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref> Alfaro was optioned back to Reading the next day. He was recalled on September 11 after the Reading season ended; he had batted .285/.325/.458 in Reading with 15 home runs (6th in the league), 67 RBIs (9th) and 105 strikeouts (tied for 5th) in 404 at bats.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=7437ec42 2016 Eastern League Batting Leaders | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20160911&content_id=200737288&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb&sid=milb |title=Phillies call up Alfaro, Quinn from Double-A |date=September 11, 2016 |accessdate=September 12, 2016 |first=Kelsie |last=Heneghan |work=MiLB.com}}</ref> He had a total of 16 major league at bats in 2016, in which he had two hits and eight strikeouts.<ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/a/alfarjo01.shtml \"Jorge Alfaro Stats\" | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nAlfaro played for [[Colombia national baseball team|Team Colombia]] in the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]].<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.mlb.com/phillies/news/phillies-jorge-alfaro-shows-off-arm-strength/c-218903312 \"Phillies Jorge Alfaro shows off arm strength\" | Philadelphia Phillies<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He entered 2017 ranked by MLB Pipeline as the No. 72 prospect, and the Phillies' No. 3 prospect.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nIn 2017 he batted .318/.360/.514 with five home runs and 14 RBIs in 107 major league at bats.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Alfaro also had the second-fastest baserunning sprint speed of all major league catchers, at 28.1 feet/second.<ref>[https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/sprint_speed_leaderboard?year=2017&position=2&team=&min=10 Statcast Sprint Speed Leaderboard | baseballsavant.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  He had the highest [[batting average on balls in play]] of all major league hitters with 100 or more at bats, at .420, swung at the highest percentage of balls outside the strike zone of all NL batters, at 46.2%, and swung and missed at an MLB-leading 21.7% of the pitches he saw.<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=100&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=12,d \"Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2017 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Dashboard\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=100&type=5&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=3,d National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2017 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=100&type=5&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=11,d \"Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2017 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> With the Class AAA [[Lehigh Valley IronPigs]] of the [[International League]], Alfaro was a mid-season All Star, and for the season he batted .241/.291/.358 with seven home runs and 43 RBIs in 324 at bats.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n[[File:Jorge Alfaro (28095386008) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Alfaro with the Phillies in 2018]]\nIn 2018 with the Phillies, Alfaro batted .262/.324/.407 with 10 home runs, 37 RBIs, and 14 [[hit by pitch]] (8th in the National League) in 344 major league at bats.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He had the highest [[batting average on balls in play]] of all major league hitters with 300 or more at bats, at .406.<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=300&type=1&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=13,d \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Advanced Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He also had the second-fastest baserunning sprint speed of all major league catchers, at 28.3 feet/second.<ref>[https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/sprint_speed_leaderboard?year=2018&position=2&team=&min=10 \"Statcast Sprint Speed Leaderboard\" | baseballsavant.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  On the other hand, he struck out 36.6% of the time, the highest rate in the National League and third-highest among all players in MLB with 300 or more plate appearances.<ref name=autogenerated8>[https://thatballsouttahere.com/2018/09/19/phillies-grading-alfaros-season/ \"Phillies: Grading Jorge Alfaro\u2019s first full season in the majors\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=350&type=8&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=10,d \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Dashboard\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He swung and missed at an MLB-leading 23.8% of the pitches he saw (the next-highest rate was [[Avisail Garcia]]'s 19.0%), and swung at the highest percentage of balls outside the strike zone of all NL batters, at 46.9% (while having the lowest contact percentage with pitches outside the strike zone of all NL batters, at 42.9%).<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=300&type=5&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=11,d \"Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/sports/csn/phillies/The_2_things_holding_Jorge_Alfaro_back_from_being_a_difference-maker.html \"The 2 Things Holding Jorge Alfaro Back From Being a Difference-maker\" - NBC 10 Philadelphia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=300&type=5&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=3,d \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=300&type=5&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=6,a \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn defense, in 2018 he had the best arm strength (90.8) and the third-best average pop time to second base (1.94 seconds) of all major league catchers, while he ranked fourth among all catchers in pitch framing according to ''[[Baseball Prospectus]]''.<ref name=autogenerated8 /> He led the NL in [[catcher's ERA]] (3.45), and his 9.11 [[range factor]] per game ranked 2nd among National League catchers.<ref>[https://thatballsouttahere.com/2018/10/05/phillies-report-card-jorge-alfaro/ \"Phillies 2018 season report card: Catcher Jorge Alfaro\"]</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>[https://www.baseballamerica.com/stories/2018-mlb-all-rookie-team/ 2018 MLB All-Rookie Team<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  However, Alfaro also led all NL catchers in [[passed ball]]s (10) and [[stolen base]]s allowed (59; though he tied for 3rd in runners [[caught stealing]] (21)), and tied for first in [[error]]s (11).<ref>[https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/poptime?year=2018&team=&min2b=10&min3b=0 Statcast Catcher Pop Time Leaderboard | baseballsavant.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=c&stats=fld&lg=nl&qual=10&type=0&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=19,d \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Catchers \u00bb Fielding Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  ''Baseball America'' named him to its 2018 MLB All-Rookie Team.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n===Miami Marlins===\nOn February 7, 2019, Alfaro was traded with [[Sixto S\u00e1nchez]], [[Will Stewart (baseball)|Will Stewart]], and $250,000 in international bonus slot money to the [[Miami Marlins]] in exchange for [[J. T. Realmuto]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Collier|first1=Jamal|title=Phillies land Realmuto for 3 players, int'l money|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jt-realmuto-phillies-marlins-trade/c-303642694?tid=282421090|website=MLB.com|publisher=[[MLB]]|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, he had the fastest sprint speed of all major league catchers, at 28.8 feet/second.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/sprint_speed_leaderboard?year=2019&position=2&team=&min=10 |title=Statcast Sprint Speed Leaderboard &#124; baseballsavant.com |publisher=Baseballsavant.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Jorge Alfaro}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=595751|espn=31737|br=a/alfarjo01|fangraphs=12180|brm=alfaro001jor|retro=A/Palfaj002}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/ea750743 Jorge Alfaro] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[http://www.pelotabinaria.com.ve/beisbol/mostrar.php?ID=alfajor001 Jorge Alfaro] at Pura Pelota (Venezuelan Professional Baseball League)\n*{{facebook|JorgeAlfaro11|Jorge Alfaro}}\n*{{twitter|_JorgeAlfaro11|Jorge Alfaro}}\n\n{{Colombia roster 2017 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Miami Marlins roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alfaro, Jorge}}\n\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sincelejo]]\n[[Category:Arizona League Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Colombian expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dominican Summer League Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Frisco RoughRiders players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Hickory Crawdads players]]\n[[Category:Lehigh Valley IronPigs players]]\n[[Category:Leones de Ponce players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from Colombia]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:Miami Marlins players]]\n[[Category:Myrtle Beach Pelicans players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Reading Fightin Phils players]]\n[[Category:Spokane Indians players]]\n[[Category:Surprise Saguaros players]]\n[[Category:Tiburones de La Guaira players]]\n[[Category:2017 World Baseball Classic players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Colombian baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Spanish name 2|Alfaro|Buelvas}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name        = Jorge Alfaro\n|image       = Jorge Alfaro (46826926795) (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = Alfaro with the Marlins in 2019\n|image_size  = 240px\n|team        = Miami Marlins\n|number      = 38\n|position    = [[Catcher]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1993|6|11}}\n|birth_place = [[Sincelejo]], [[Colombia]]\n|bats        = Right\n|throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate   = September 12\n|debutyear   = 2016\n|debutteam   = Philadelphia Phillies\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|statleague  = MLB\n|stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value  = .266\n|stat3label  = [[Home run]]s\n|stat3value  = 33\n|stat4label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value  = 108\n|awards      = \n|teams       = \n*[[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|2016}}\u2013{{mlby|2018}})\n*[[Miami Marlins]] ({{mlby|2019}}\u2013present)\n}}\n'''Jorge Mario Alfaro Buelvas''' (born June 11, 1993) is a [[Colombians|Colombian]] [[professional baseball]] [[catcher]] for the [[Miami Marlins]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Alfaro signed with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] as a [[free agent]] in 2010, and was traded to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] in 2015. He made his MLB debut in 2016.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nAlfaro was born in [[Sincelejo]], [[Colombia]]. Alfaro's younger brother Jhoandro is a catcher in the [[Chicago White Sox]] organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/international/white-sox-sign-colombian-catcher-jhoandro-alfaro/|title=White Sox Sign Colombian Catcher Jhoandro Alfaro|first1=Ben|last1=Badler|date=July 2, 2014|website=baseballamerica.com|accessdate=June 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=alfaro000jho|title=Jhoandro Alfaro Minor Leagues Statistics & History|website=baseball-reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|access-date=August 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated6>[https://www.mlb.com/player/jorge-alfaro-595751 \"Jorge Alfaro Stats, Fantasy & News\" | MLB.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Alfaro played baseball and soccer at Instituto T\u00e9cnico Industrial Antonio Prieto, graduating in 2009.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==Career==\n===Texas Rangers organization===\nAlfaro signed with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in June 2010 as a 16-year-old [[free agent]] for a $1.3 million [[signing bonus]] that was a record at the time for any Colombian prospect.<ref>[https://thatballsouttahere.com/2016/02/10/phillies-top-10-prospects-6-jorge-alfaro/ \"Phillies Top 10 Prospects: #6 \u2013 Jorge Alfaro\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?sid=milb&player_id=595751#/career/R/hitting/2018/ALL \"Jorge Alfaro Stats, Highlights, Bio\" | MiLB.com Stats | The Official Site of Minor League Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated7>[https://www.lonestarball.com/2013/2/7/3961876/jorge-alfaro-scouting-report \"Jorge Alfaro Scouting Report\" - Lone Star Ball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2010, playing for the [[DSL Rangers]] in the [[Dominican Summer League]] he batted .221/.278/.291 with one [[home run]] and 23 [[RBI]]s.<ref name=autogenerated5>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=alfaro001jor \"Jorge Alfaro Minor, Winter & Fall Leagues Statistics & History\" | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn 2011, playing for the Class A Short-Season [[Spokane Indians]] in the [[Northwest League]], Alfaro batted .300/.345/.481 (9th in the league) with six home runs, 23 RBIs, and seven [[hit by pitch]] (6th) in 160 [[at bat]]s, as on defense he allowed 12 [[passed ball]]s and made 10 [[error]]s in 36 games at catcher.<ref name=autogenerated6 />  He was a ''[[Baseball America]]'' Short-Season All Star and a [[Topps]] Short-Season/Rookie All Star, and ''Baseball America'' named him the 8th-best prospect in the Northwest League.<ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=595751#/career/R/hitting/2018/ALL \"Jorge Alfaro Stats, Highlights, Bio\" | MiLB.com Stats | The Official Site of Minor League Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nIn 2012, playing for the Class A [[Hickory Crawdads]] in the [[South Atlantic League]], he batted .261/.320/.430 with five home runs and 34 RBIs in 272 at bats.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> ''Baseball America'' rated Alfaro the 9th-best Rangers prospect.<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\nPrior to the 2013 season Alfaro was ranked by [[MLB.com]] as the 88th-best prospect in baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130129&content_id=41240146&c_id=tex |first1=T.R. |last1=Sullivan |title=Rangers have six of game's Top 100 Prospects |publisher=MLB Advanced Media |website=rangers.mlb.com |date=January 29, 2013 |accessdate=December 14, 2013}}</ref> Alfaro was ranked the 54th-best prospect by ''Baseball America''. In 2013, playing for Hickory in the South Atlantic League, he was a mid-season All Star, an MiLB.com Texas Organization All Star, and an [[All-Star Futures Game]] selection.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> He batted .258/.338/.452 with 16 home runs, 53 RBIs, and 18 hit by pitch (leading the league) in 372 at bats, as on defense he allowed 26 passed balls and made 10 errors in 82 games at catcher.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> ''Baseball America'' named him the 14th-best prospect in the South Atlantic League.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> He also had 21 at bats with the [[AZL Rangers]], and 11 at bats with the [[Myrtle Beach Pelicans]].<ref name=autogenerated5 /> After the 2013 season he played for the [[Surprise Saguaros]] in the [[Arizona Fall League]], where he was batted .386 (3rd in the league)/.438 (9th)/.500 with 18 runs (5th), six [[double (baseball)|double]]s (6th), 11 RBIs, and three hit by pitch (2nd) in 70 at bats.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> He was named both a Rising Star and to the All-Prospect Team.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/11/texas-rangers-catching-prospect-shows-off-arm-in-afl.html/ |title=Texas Rangers catching prospect Jorge Alfaro shows off arm in AFL |publisher=Rangersblog.dallasnews.com |date=November 18, 2013 |accessdate=December 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214223048/http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/11/texas-rangers-catching-prospect-shows-off-arm-in-afl.html/ |archivedate=December 14, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/08/catcher-jorge-alfaro-heads-texas-rangers-list-of-prospects-in-arizona-fall-league.html/|title=Catcher Jorge Alfaro heads Texas Rangers list of prospects in Arizona Fall League|date=August 27, 2013|work=dallasnews.com|accessdate=June 28, 2016|first1=Evan|last1=Grant|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219021643/http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/08/catcher-jorge-alfaro-heads-texas-rangers-list-of-prospects-in-arizona-fall-league.html/|archive-date=February 19, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 playing for Class A-Advanced Myrtle Beach he was [[Carolina League]] Player of the Week on August 4, a mid-season All Star, an MiLB Texas Organization All Star, and a post-season All Star.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> Alfaro was also the starting catcher for the World Squad at the [[All-Star Futures Game]].<ref name=autogenerated6 />  For the season, he batted .261/.318/.440 with five triples (10th in the league), 13 home runs (6th), 73 RBIs (3rd), and 12 hit by pitch (4th), as on defense he allowed 18 passed balls and made 13 errors at catcher in 75 games.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> ''Baseball America'' named him the second-best prospect in the Carolina League.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> He also had 88 at bats with the Double-A [[Frisco RoughRiders]] of the [[Texas League]], batting .261/.343/.443 with four home runs and 14 RBIs.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\nOn November 20, 2014, the Rangers added Alfaro to their [[40-man roster]] to protect him from being selected in the [[Rule 5 draft]].<ref>[https://nolanwritin.com/2014/11/19/rule-5-draft-texas-rangers-must-finalize-40-man-roster-by-thursday-jorge-alfaro/ \"Rule-5 Draft: Texas Rangers must finalize 40-man roster by Thursday\"]</ref> In 2015 playing for Frisco he was a mid-season All Star, and batted .253/.314/.432 with five home runs and 21 RBIs in 190 at bats.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n===Philadelphia Phillies===\nOn July 31, 2015, the Rangers traded Alfaro, [[Nick Williams (baseball)|Nick Williams]], [[Matt Harrison (baseball)|Matt Harrison]], [[Jake Thompson]], [[Alec Asher]], and [[Jerad Eickhoff]] to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for [[Cole Hamels]] and [[Jake Diekman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/majors/trade-central-hamels-texas-ranger/|title=Trade Central: Phillies Get Impact Talent, Depth In Hamels Deal|first=Ben|last=Badler|website=baseballamerica.com|date=July 31, 2015|accessdate=July 31, 2015}}</ref> In the remainder of 2015 he had four at bats with the [[GCL Phillies]].<ref name=autogenerated5 /> ''Baseball America'' named him the 5th-best prospect in the Phillies minor league system.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nIn 2016 playing for the Double-A [[Reading Fightin Phils]] he was an [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] Player of the Week and Phillies Minor League Player of the Week on April 17, Phillies Minor League Defender of the Month for July, a mid-season All Star, and an MiLB Philadelphia Organization All Star.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref name=autogenerated6 />  The Phillies promoted Alfaro to the major leagues on August 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/197781550/phillies-call-no-4-prospect-jorge-alfaro/|title=Phillies call up No. 4 prospect Jorge Alfaro|first1=Joshua|last1=Needelman|website=mlb.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref> Alfaro was optioned back to Reading the next day. He was recalled on September 11 after the Reading season ended; he had batted .285/.325/.458 in Reading with 15 home runs (6th in the league), 67 RBIs (9th) and 105 strikeouts (tied for 5th) in 404 at bats.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=7437ec42 2016 Eastern League Batting Leaders | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20160911&content_id=200737288&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb&sid=milb |title=Phillies call up Alfaro, Quinn from Double-A |date=September 11, 2016 |accessdate=September 12, 2016 |first=Kelsie |last=Heneghan |work=MiLB.com}}</ref> He had a total of 16 major league at bats in 2016, in which he had two hits and eight strikeouts.<ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/a/alfarjo01.shtml \"Jorge Alfaro Stats\" | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nAlfaro played for [[Colombia national baseball team|Team Colombia]] in the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]].<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.mlb.com/phillies/news/phillies-jorge-alfaro-shows-off-arm-strength/c-218903312 \"Phillies Jorge Alfaro shows off arm strength\" | Philadelphia Phillies<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He entered 2017 ranked by MLB Pipeline as the No. 72 prospect, and the Phillies' No. 3 prospect.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nIn 2017 he batted .318/.360/.514 with five home runs and 14 RBIs in 107 major league at bats.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Alfaro also had the second-fastest baserunning sprint speed of all major league catchers, at 28.1 feet/second.<ref>[https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/sprint_speed_leaderboard?year=2017&position=2&team=&min=10 Statcast Sprint Speed Leaderboard | baseballsavant.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  He had the highest [[batting average on balls in play]] of all major league hitters with 100 or more at bats, at .420, swung at the highest percentage of balls outside the strike zone of all NL batters, at 46.2%, and swung and missed at an MLB-leading 21.7% of the pitches he saw.<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=100&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=12,d \"Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2017 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Dashboard\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=100&type=5&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=3,d National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2017 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=100&type=5&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=11,d \"Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2017 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> With the Class AAA [[Lehigh Valley IronPigs]] of the [[International League]], Alfaro was a mid-season All Star, and for the season he batted .241/.291/.358 with seven home runs and 43 RBIs in 324 at bats.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n[[File:Jorge Alfaro (28095386008) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Alfaro with the Phillies in 2018]]\nIn 2018 with the Phillies, Alfaro batted .262/.324/.407 with 10 home runs, 37 RBIs, and 14 [[hit by pitch]] (8th in the National League) in 344 major league at bats.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He had the highest [[batting average on balls in play]] of all major league hitters with 300 or more at bats, at .406.<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=300&type=1&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=13,d \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Advanced Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He also had the second-fastest baserunning sprint speed of all major league catchers, at 28.3 feet/second.<ref>[https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/sprint_speed_leaderboard?year=2018&position=2&team=&min=10 \"Statcast Sprint Speed Leaderboard\" | baseballsavant.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  On the other hand, he struck out 36.6% of the time, the highest rate in the National League and third-highest among all players in MLB with 300 or more plate appearances.<ref name=autogenerated8>[https://thatballsouttahere.com/2018/09/19/phillies-grading-alfaros-season/ \"Phillies: Grading Jorge Alfaro\u2019s first full season in the majors\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=350&type=8&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=10,d \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Dashboard\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He swung and missed at an MLB-leading 23.8% of the pitches he saw (the next-highest rate was [[Avisail Garcia]]'s 19.0%), and swung at the highest percentage of balls outside the strike zone of all NL batters, at 46.9% (while having the lowest contact percentage with pitches outside the strike zone of all NL batters, at 42.9%).<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=300&type=5&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=11,d \"Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/sports/csn/phillies/The_2_things_holding_Jorge_Alfaro_back_from_being_a_difference-maker.html \"The 2 Things Holding Jorge Alfaro Back From Being a Difference-maker\" - NBC 10 Philadelphia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=300&type=5&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=3,d \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=nl&qual=300&type=5&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=6,a \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Plate Discipline Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn defense, in 2018 he had the best arm strength (90.8) and the third-best average pop time to second base (1.94 seconds) of all major league catchers, while he ranked fourth among all catchers in pitch framing according to ''[[Baseball Prospectus]]''.<ref name=autogenerated8 /> He led the NL in [[catcher's ERA]] (3.45), and his 9.11 [[range factor]] per game ranked 2nd among National League catchers.<ref>[https://thatballsouttahere.com/2018/10/05/phillies-report-card-jorge-alfaro/ \"Phillies 2018 season report card: Catcher Jorge Alfaro\"]</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>[https://www.baseballamerica.com/stories/2018-mlb-all-rookie-team/ 2018 MLB All-Rookie Team<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  However, Alfaro also led all NL catchers in [[passed ball]]s (10) and [[stolen base]]s allowed (59; though he tied for 3rd in runners [[caught stealing]] (21)), and tied for first in [[error]]s (11).<ref>[https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/poptime?year=2018&team=&min2b=10&min3b=0 Statcast Catcher Pop Time Leaderboard | baseballsavant.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=c&stats=fld&lg=nl&qual=10&type=0&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=19,d \"National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Catchers \u00bb Fielding Statistics\" | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  ''Baseball America'' named him to its 2018 MLB All-Rookie Team.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n===Miami Marlins===\nOn February 7, 2019, Alfaro was traded with [[Sixto S\u00e1nchez]], [[Will Stewart (baseball)|Will Stewart]], and $250,000 in international bonus slot money to the [[Miami Marlins]] in exchange for [[J. T. Realmuto]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Collier|first1=Jamal|title=Phillies land Realmuto for 3 players, int'l money|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jt-realmuto-phillies-marlins-trade/c-303642694?tid=282421090|website=MLB.com|publisher=[[MLB]]|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, he had the fastest sprint speed of all major league catchers, at 28.8 feet/second.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/sprint_speed_leaderboard?year=2019&position=2&team=&min=10 |title=Statcast Sprint Speed Leaderboard &#124; baseballsavant.com |publisher=Baseballsavant.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Jorge Alfaro}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=595751|espn=31737|br=a/alfarjo01|fangraphs=12180|brm=alfaro001jor|retro=A/Palfaj002}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/ea750743 Jorge Alfaro] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[http://www.pelotabinaria.com.ve/beisbol/mostrar.php?ID=alfajor001 Jorge Alfaro] at Pura Pelota (Venezuelan Professional Baseball League)\n*{{facebook|JorgeAlfaro11|Jorge Alfaro}}\n*{{twitter|_JorgeAlfaro11|Jorge Alfaro}}\n\n{{Colombia roster 2017 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Miami Marlins roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alfaro, Jorge}}\n\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Arizona League Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Colombian expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dominican Summer League Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Frisco RoughRiders players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Hickory Crawdads players]]\n[[Category:Lehigh Valley IronPigs players]]\n[[Category:Leones de Ponce players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from Colombia]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:Miami Marlins players]]\n[[Category:Myrtle Beach Pelicans players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Reading Fightin Phils players]]\n[[Category:Spokane Indians players]]\n[[Category:Surprise Saguaros players]]\n[[Category:Tiburones de La Guaira players]]\n[[Category:2017 World Baseball Classic players]]\n", "name_user": "Inter&anthro", "label": "safe", "comment": "says it in the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jorge_Alfaro"}
{"title_page": "Quinten Hann", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n|name = Quinten Hann\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|6|4}}\n|birth_place =[[Wagga Wagga]], [[New South Wales]]\n| Sport country= {{AUS}}\n| Nickname = The Wizard of Oz\n| Professional = 1995\u20132006\n| High ranking = 14 (2002\u20132004)\n| Century break = 41<ref name=\"centurybreaks\">{{cite web|title=Centuries|url=http://www.prosnookerblog.com/centuries/|website=Pro Snooker Blog|accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n| Prize money = [[Pound sterling|GB\u00a3]]432,600\n| High break = '''143''': <br> <small>1997 Grand Prix</small>\n| Best finish = Semi-final <small>([[Irish Masters (snooker)|2004 Irish Masters]])</small>\n| Ranking wins =\n| Other wins =\n}}\n'''Quinten Hann''' (born 4 June 1977) is an Australian former professional [[snooker]] player. He was the 1999 [[List of world eight-ball champions|WEPF World Eight-ball Champion]] and 1994 world under 21 champion. His highest break was a 143 that he made at the [[1997 Grand Prix (snooker)|1997 Grand Prix]] tournament. He was given an eight-year ban from snooker in February 2006 for match-fixing at the [[2005 China Open (snooker)|2005 China Open]], shortly before which he had resigned his membership of the [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] (WPBSA).\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and amateur career===\nBorn on 4 June 1977 in [[Wagga Wagga]], [[New South Wales]],<ref name=MRHoF/> Hann is the only child in a single parent family;<ref name=\"AgeApr98\" /> his father was absent from his life after they separated during the family's time in [[Melbourne]].<ref name=\"AgeApr98\" /><ref name=SMApr02>{{Cite news|last=Schlink|first=Leo|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85143514/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=04ceb7ac|title=Ex-Queensland boy shakes up snooker world \u2013 Loose cannon|date=28 April 2002|work=[[The Sunday Mail (Brisbane)|The Sunday Mail]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=026|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He was educated at the city's [[Samaritan Catholic College|Redden Catholic College]].<ref name=SMApr02/> Hann's mother Amanda purchased a [[Billiard table|snooker table]] for him to practise on when he turned nine.<ref name=\"AgeApr98\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/122858950/|title=Snooker's Melbourne demon|last=Hanlon|first=Peter|date=26 April 1998|work=[[The Age|The Sunday Age]]|access-date=30 September 2019|page=19|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He later took up [[Pool (cue sports)|pool]] at the age of ten after being introduced to it through a friend in [[Brisbane]].<ref name=\"SHFeb91\">{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A297577824/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=477e8786|title=At 13, Quinten Hann just wants to pot gold|date=3 February 1991|work=The Sun-Herald|access-date=15 March 2019|page=81|url-access=subscription |via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Hann played pool during the weekends, until his mother swayed him away from playing it in [[Pub|public houses]]. She telephoned a snooker coach to teach her son the game.<ref name=\"MNApr98\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.messengernewspapers.co.uk/news/7234980.YOUNG_snooker_star_Quinten_Hann_is_hoping_to_follow_the_yellow_brick_road_all_the_way_to_the_top_/|title=Young snooker star Quinten Hann is hoping to follow the yellow brick road all the way to the top|date=9 April 1998|work=Sale & Altrincham Messenger|access-date=15 March 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930175954/https://www.messengernewspapers.co.uk/news/7234980.young-snooker-star-quinten-hann-is-hoping-to-follow-the-yellow-brick-road-all-the-way-to-the-top/|archive-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nAt age 12, Hann became the youngest qualifier for the [[Australian Goldfields Open]] in June 1989, losing in the last 16 stage to the under-21 national champion [[Steve Mifsud]]. Although he broke his left wrist in a motorcycle accident, which caused him to play in a plaster, he won the Victoria Under-12 Championship in March 1990. Three months later, Hann finished runner-up in his group at the 1990 [[IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship]], with six victories from eight matches.<ref name=\"SHFeb91\" /> Hann's mother sold the family home and car and possessions to finance her son's career and moved them from Wagga Wagga to England in late 1989.<ref name=SHFeb91/><ref name=GuardianJan91>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A171221043/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=d600ab9a|title=Snooker: Hann's TV spectacular|last=Everton|first=Clive|date=21 January 1991|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2019|page=13|url-access=subscription |via=General OneFile}}</ref> She had written to [[Matchroom Sport]] founder [[Barry Hearn]], who offered his services to Hann.<ref name=SHFeb91/>  \n\nAt the age of 13, Hann produced a break of 100 at the [[1991 World Masters]] under-16 tournament, making him the youngest player to compile a televised [[century break]].<ref name=\"GuardianJan91\" /> He reached the final of the Australian Amateur Championship at age 14 and he then took part in the [[IBSF World Snooker Championship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A170911444/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=8e326611|title=Sport: Sixth Column|date=29 May 1993|work=The Guardian|access-date=16 March 2019|page=19|url-access=subscription |via=General OneFile}}</ref> On 13 October 1991, Hann was given a suspended ban by the Australian Billiards and Snooker Council from all domestic and overseas competitions for spitting on a competitor's mother. This was invoked after the New South Wales country junior championship in January 1993 when he swore at the referee following a decision that favoured his opponent and entered the Lithgow Workmen's Club licensed poker-machine area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/120521943/|title=Bad boy of snooker is grounded|date=14 March 1993|work=Sunday Age|access-date=16 March 2019|page=24|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The ban was appealed by Hann's family to the [[High Court of Australia]]; it was reduced to one year.<ref name=TimesApr98>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A59979532/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=1fcc2b2f|title=1998 Embassy World Championship; Snooker|last=Yates|first=Phil|date=18 April 1998|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=1 October 2019|page=35|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In the meantime, he won the 1992 Australian Open 8-ball Championship, defeating Lou Condo 6\u20131 in the final and later beat [[David Gray (snooker player)|David Gray]] 11\u201310 to win the 1994 IBSF World Under-21 Championship.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A103932605/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=191e1031|title=Hann's shot at the big time / Inside Back|last=Kershler|first=Ray|date=4 April 1998|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 March 2019|page=151|url-access=subscription |via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\n===Professional career===\nHann became a professional player in 1995.<ref name=MRHoF>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museumriverina.com.au/collections/hall-of-fame/inductees/hann,-quinte|title=Quinten Hann|work=Museum of the Riverina|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324000147/http://www.museumriverina.com.au/collections/hall-of-fame/inductees/hann,-quinte|archive-date=24 March 2017|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> In five months of his first season, he reached {{Abbr|No.|World ranking nunber}} 237 in the world by competing in satellite tournaments.<ref name=\"DTMar98\" /> Not discouraged by this, he met Brandon Parker through another player; Parker agreed to manage Hann's career.<ref name=\"MNApr98\" /> Hann was now able to enter tournaments abroad in the [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/1997 season]], reaching the quarter-finals of the [[1997 Thailand Open]], and rising to No. 104 in the world.<ref name=\"DTMar98\">{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A103934862/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=7db4d773|title=Hann is snooker's new man|last=Kershler|first=Ray|date=27 March 1998|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=1 October 2019|page=115|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 1996, he was paired with [[Robby Foldvari]] and [[Stan Gorski]] to represent Australia at the [[1996 World Cup (snooker)|Snooker World Cup]]. The trio lasted until the quarter-finals, being defeated 5\u201310 by England.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/260444462/|title=Bond broken by Australian welder|last=Everton|first=Clive|date=7 November 1996|work=The Guardian|access-date=30 September 2019|page=24|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> \n\nFor the [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/1998 season]], Hann reached the televised stages of more tournaments, lasting until the second-rounds of the [[1997 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] (where he set a record of 13 consecutive victories with a 5\u20134 margin and compiled the highest break of his career, a 143),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/9798/gp97_res.shtml|title=Grand Prix 1997|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12287044.higgins-is-handed-win-hann-blows-his-act-by-showboating/|title=Higgins is handed win Hann blows his act by showboating|date=21 October 1997|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|access-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001131511/https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12287044.higgins-is-handed-win-hann-blows-his-act-by-showboating/|archive-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> the [[1997 UK Championship|UK Championship]],<ref name=\"TimesApr98\" /> and the [[1997 German Open (snooker)|German Open]] tournaments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/9798/go97_res.shtml|title=German Open 1997|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> He lost in the first round of the preliminary stages of the [[1998 British Open|British Open]] with a 5\u20130 [[Whitewash (sport)|whitewash]] to [[Drew Henry]] in April 1998.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-hann-suffers-heaviest-defeat-of-season-1154189.html|title=Snooker: Hann suffers heaviest defeat of season|date=3 April 1998|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> One month earlier, Hann became the first Australian player since [[Eddie Charlton]] in 1992 to qualify for the [[1998 World Snooker Championship|World Snooker Championship]].<ref name=\"TimesApr98\" /> He was eliminated by [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 9\u201310 in the first round,<ref name=\"AgeApr98\" /> ending the season ranked No. 45 in the world.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" />\n\nHann won the Lindrum Masters multi-format tournament in [[Newcastle, New South Wales]] in September 1998. After the tournament, he met with his mother and World Snooker chairman [[Rex Williams]], and agreed to change his lifestyle and public image.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A103859017/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=674ff5c2|title=Bad boy is shaping up / Inside Back|last=Kershler|first=Ray|date=7 November 1998|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=30 September 2019|page=159|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Hann advanced to the quarter-finals of the [[1998 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] tournament in the following month,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A91704804/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=f9dfa5e8|title=Snooker|date=21 October 1998|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|access-date=1 October 2019|page=110|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> losing to [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] in a 5\u20130 whitewash.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-lee-is-far-too-hot-for-hann-1180084.html|title=Snooker: Lee is far too hot for Hann|date=23 October 1998|work=The Independent|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> He lost 5\u20139 to Marcus Campbell in the second round of the [[1998 UK Championship|UK Championship]] in November; Hann's opponent criticised him for conceding two [[Glossary_of_cue_sports_terms#frame|frames]] in the match.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A82949160/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=634d0216|title=Campbell gets the breaks as Hann makes a spectacle|last=Baxter|first=Trevor|date=23 November 1998|work=[[The Scotsman]]|access-date=1 October 2019|page=32|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Hann replicated this performance once more during the season, this time in the [[1999 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] in February 1999, losing 2\u20135 to [[Graeme Dott]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-hanns-theatrics-earn-a-rebuke-1071638.html|title=Snooker: Hann's theatrics earn a rebuke|date=18 February 1999|work=The Independent|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> He concluded the season ranked No. 26 in the world.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> \n\nBefore the start of the [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/2000 snooker season]], Hann won the [[WEPF World Eight-ball championship|WEPF World 8-Ball Pool Championship]] to become the only player born outside the United Kingdom and Ireland to claim the title,<ref>{{Cite journal|date=October 2013|title=How the World Began|url=https://issuu.com/bud144/docs/magazine_ed_6_v3_layout_1|journal=World Pool Magazine|edition=6|pages=21|access-date=1 October 2019|via=[[Issuu]]}}</ref> and defeated [[Oliver Ortmann]] to successfully defend the Lindrum Masters tournament in August.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.snookerimages.co.uk/news.html|title=Hann triumphs again|last=Dee|first=John|date=13 August 1999|access-date=1 October 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19991008212759/http://www.snookerimages.co.uk/news.html|archive-date=8 October 1999|website=Snooker Images}}</ref> He qualified for the [[1999 British Open (1999/2000)|British Open]] in September, lasting until the second round when he was defeated 2\u20135 by Stephen Lee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/9900/bo99_res.shtml|title=British Open 1999 (autumn)|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> In October Hann withdrew from the [[1999 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] due to his father suffering a myocardial infarction,<ref name=IndyNov99>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-hanns-year-ends-early-1126525.html|title=Snooker: Hann's year ends early|date=16 November 1999|work=The Independent|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> and then the Australian Nine-Ball Championship to pursue riding motorcycles as a hobby.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85449031/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=f3de8b33|title=Nine-Ball Showdown|last=Clancy|first=Brett|date=29 October 1999|work=The Advertiser|access-date=1 October 2019|page=093|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> While doing this, he sustained a [[clavicle fracture]] and a bruised wrist in an accident in Melbourne,<ref name=IndyNov99/><ref name=GuardianOct00>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/story/0,3604,376486,00.html|title=Hann takes his cue from Australia's golden haul|last=Everton|first=Clive|date=3 October 2000|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001142527/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/story/0,3604,376486,00.html|archive-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> requiring him to not partake in the next six tournaments as he recovered from the injuries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2006/0215/201395-hann/|title=Hann quits snooker|date=15 February 2006|access-date=1 October 2019|work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]}}</ref> Hann returned to competition at the [[2000 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] in March 2000, reaching the second-round where he lost 4\u20135 to eventual champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A61404483/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=042ec2ea|title=Maximum impact by O'Sullivan; Snooker|date=6 April 2000|work=The Times|access-date=1 October 2019|page=31|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> \n\nHe began the [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/2001 season]] ranked world No. 32.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> Hann prepared for the upcoming campaign by increasing his practise at his home in Melbourne.<ref name=GuardianOct00/> Before that Hann lasted until the semi-final stage of the World 8-Ball Championship in June 2000.<ref name=110Profile>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/php/SnookerProfiles/viewsnook.php?p_id=28|title=Quinten Hann: At A Glance|website=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040218101150/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/php/SnookerProfiles/viewsnook.php?p_id=28|archive-date=18 February 2004|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann was eliminated from the second round at the Grand Prix tournament,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yates|first=Phil|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A66225251/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=76f29654|title=Angry Hann sees red; Snooker|date=19 October 2000|work=The Times|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=37|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and was booed by spectators for smashing the [[Billiard ball|cue ball]] into the pack of {{Cuegloss|red ball|reds}} in the final three frames of his match against O'Sullivan.<ref name=SMHApr02>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/australian-hope-nears-meltdown-at-the-crucible-20020425-gdf83u.html|title=Australian hope nears meltdown at The Crucible|date=25 April 2002|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He earned an official reprimand of \u00a3750 for \"unprofessional behaviour\" for nonperformance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/413.htm|title=Aussie Hann Loses Some Of His Grand Prix Prize Money|last=Dee|first=John|date=8 January 2001|work=Embassy Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010429054525/http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/413.htm|archive-date=29 April 2001|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann broke a bone in his foot in a [[parachuting|parachute jump]] before the [[2000 UK Championship]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nelson|first=Kevin|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A67368922/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=434f9e7d|title=Snooker: Pain and gain for hobbling Hann|date=28 November 2000|work=The Independent|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=27|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and was required to play shoeless in a tournament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/in_depth/2000/uk_championship_snooker/1036217.stm|title=High, wide and Hann-some|last=Everton|first=Clive|date=22 November 2000|work=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> where he lasted until the quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Everton|first=Clive|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A75684685/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=82e067a4|title=Snooker: O'Sullivan plays safe to leave Hann in awe|date=1 December 2000|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=36|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He also reached the quarter-finals of the [[2001 Thailand Masters|Thailand Masters]] before losing to [[John Parrott]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0001/tm2001_res.shtml|title=Blue Eagle/Thai Airways Thailand Masters 2001|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann qualified for the [[2001 World Snooker Championship]] and was drawn against world number 16 [[Dave Harold]] in the first round.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kershler|first=Ray|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A103584316/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=41a151fb|title=Hann no fall guy this time|date=29 March 2001|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=044|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The match saw Hann lose 5\u201310 to Harold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/in_depth/2001/world_snooker_championship/1291048.stm|title=Harold outguns Aussie Hann|date=22 April 2001|work=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021106173039/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/in_depth/2001/world_snooker_championship/1291048.stm|archive-date=6 November 2002|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe commenced the [[2001\u201302 snooker season|2001/2002 season]] as the world number 25.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> Hann reached the second round of the season's first three ranking tournaments,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/581.htm|title=Alan McManus Outpots Aussie Quinten Hann|last=Dee|first=John|date=3 October 2001|work=Embassy Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011005014226/http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/581.htm|archive-date=5 October 2001|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Yates|first=Phil|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A79216641/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=86ac9d60|title=Williams silences Hann with limp effort; Snooker|date=17 October 2001|work=The Times|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=8|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na04789.php|title=\"Grateful\" Doherty Flattens Hann|last=Hendon|first=David|date=25 November 2001|website=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011201064933/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na04789.php|archive-date=1 December 2001|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> before improving his performance to last until the third round of the [[2002 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] and the [[2002 Thailand Masters|Thailand Masters]].<ref name=110Profile/> By progressing beyond the third round of the [[2002 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] later in 2002, he ensured that he would end the season as one of the world's top sixteen ranked players, the first time this had happened for an Australian player since [[Eddie Charlton]] in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dee|first=John|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/3025707/Snooker-Hann-breaks-into-top-16.html|title=Snooker: Hann breaks into top 16|date=10 April 2002|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hann ended the tournament in the quarter-final stage and critiqued the World Snooker Association's running of snooker.<ref name=110Profile/> He concluded the season in the second round of the World Snooker Championship with a victory over [[Paul Hunter (snooker player)|Paul Hunter]] in the first round and a loss to Stephen Lee in the next stage.<ref name=110Profile/> Players and pundits criticised Hann for breaking up the red balls in a pool-style method during both of his matches and for unprofessional-ism in the second game.<ref name=SMHApr02/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/extrovert-aussie-knocked-out-in-second-round-20020501-gdf8n7.html|title=Extrovert Aussie knocked out in second round|date=1 May 2002|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Australian Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2002\u201303 snooker season|2002/2003 season]] saw Hann begin as a player who was ranked 14th in the world.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> He was unable to win a match in the season's first four ranking tournaments.<ref name=\"MRHoF\" /> Hann's top sixteen world ranking allowed him to enter the non-ranking [[2003 Masters (snooker)|Masters tournament]] for the first time in his professional career,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burnside|first=Brian|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A88452030/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=725fdad5|title=Snooker: Hann awaits return to top-level competition|date=6 July 2002|work=The Independent|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=9|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> losing in the first round 4\u20136 to Lee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0203/bm2003_res.shtml|title=Benson & Hedges Masters 2003|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> This marked a turning point in his season as he reached the second round of the next two competitions and the quarter-finals of the [[2003 Irish Masters]].<ref name=\"MRHoF\" /> At the [[2003 World Snooker Championship|World Snooker Championship]], Hann defeated Parrott 10\u20135 in the first round,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/957.htm|title=Hann Takes Care Of Parrott's Challenge|last=Dee|first=John|date=20 April 2003|work=Embassy Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030608115619/http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/957.htm|archive-date=8 June 2003|access-date=21 February 2003}}</ref> before he was defeated by Mark Williams 13\u20132 in the second round.<ref>{{cite news|last=Warren|first=Dan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/2980353.stm|title=Williams powers past Hann|date=28 April 2003|accessdate=19 March 2011|url-status=live|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nHe retained his ranking of 14th in the world for the [[2003\u201304 snooker season|2003/2004 season]].<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> Hann moved to Ealing after the 2003 world championship and began practising regularly at Ealing Snooker Club in a bid to establish himself as one of the world's top 16 players.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mistry|first=Ushma|url=https://www.ealingtimes.co.uk/sport/454639.hann-ealing-move-could-save-my-game/|title=Hann: Ealing move could save my game|date=29 January 2004|work=Ealing Times|access-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He got through to the quarter-finals of the [[2003 UK Championship|UK Championship]] for the first time, where he played Ronnie O'Sullivan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/snooker-practice-makes-perfect-hann-1670109|title=Snooker: Practice makes perfect for Hann|date=25 November 2003|work=[[Evening Chronicle]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He lost the match 3\u20139.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A110830104/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=6a5b6e56|title=Hann crushed by O'Sullivan|date=29 November 2003|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=095|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> At the [[2004 Masters (snooker)|2004 Masters]], Hann was defeated in the first round 3\u20136 by [[Peter Ebdon]].<ref name=\"BBCEbdonHann\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/3460173.stm|title=Ebdon eases past Hann|date=4 February 2004|access-date=9 February 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212012442/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/3460173.stm|archive-date=12 February 2019|work=BBC Sport|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He later progressed to the quarter-finals of the [[2004 European Open (snooker)|European Open]] in Malta and lost to local player [[Tony Drago]] 1\u20135.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0304/eo2004_res.shtml|title=European Open 2004|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann progressed into the first ranking semi-final of his professional career at the [[2004 Irish Masters|Irish Masters]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dee|first=John|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A114660218/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=ebc73e32|title=Hann in last four|date=27 March 2004|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> This made him the first Australian player to reach the semi-finals of a tournament since [[Warren King (snooker player)|Warren King]] at the [[1990 Classic (snooker)|1990 Classic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/snooker/hann-reaches-masters-final-140120.html|title=Hann reaches Masters final|date=26 March 2004|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hann conceded a frame while 30\u201324 ahead and executed a pool-style break off in his 5\u20136 defeat to Ebdon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/3575755.stm|title=Ebdon edges out Hann|date=28 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nHis final match of the season was a 4\u201310 defeat to [[Andy Hicks]] in the first round of the [[2004 World Snooker Championship|World Snooker Championship]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Yates|first=Phil|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A115536038/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=1fe35ca1|title=Defeated Hann displays his ugly side again; Snooker|date=19 April 2004|work=The Times|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=36|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> After the match referee Lawrie Annandale separated the two players from having a physical alteration after Hann made a threatening comment to Hicks when the latter suggested he would lose his top 16 world ranking.<ref name=\":0\" /> He challenged Hicks to a fight; In the event fellow snooker player [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]] stood in for Hicks at a charity boxing match with Hann which the latter won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/funny_old_game/3797515.stm |title=Hann triumphs in Pot Whack |work=BBC Sport |date=12 June 2004 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> Hann also fought [[Dublin GAA]] player, [[Johnny Magee]], in a charity boxing match in Dublin in September 2004 after He suggested that [[Gaelic football]]ers were not as robust as Australia [[Australian rules football|rules footballers]]. He had his nose broken, with Magee winning in three rounds.<ref name=\"accidents\">{{cite web|url=http://www.breakingnews.ie/2006/02/14/story244688.html|title=Hann's controversial career seems over|date=14 February 2006|website=BreakingNews.ie|publisher=[[Thomas Crosbie Holdings]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311033533/http://www.breakingnews.ie/2006/02/14/story244688.html|archivedate=11 March 2007|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bunce |first=Jane |title=Hann lost for cash \u2013 report |date=11 May 2005 |website= theage.com.au |publisher=[[The Age|The Age Company]] |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Sport/Hann-lost-for-cash--report/2005/05/10/1115584957599.html |accessdate=22 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nHann fell to 18th in the world rankings before the commencement of the [[2004\u201305 snooker season|2004/2005 season]].<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> He reached the quarter finals of the 2004 World 8-Ball Championship and lost 6\u20139 to [[Darren Appleton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kozoom.com/en/pool-billiard/players/hann-quinten/matches.html|title=Player US Pool: Quinten Hann|website=Kozoom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann withdrew from the [[2005 Malta Cup]] because he had a fractured finger.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.smh.com.au/sport/haan-pulls-out-of-malta-cup-20050203-gdkmay.html|title=Haan pulls out of Malta Cup|date=3 February 2005|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|agency=Press Association}}</ref> The [[2005 World Snooker Championship|2005 World Championship]] saw Hann forced to play with a new [[Cue stick|cue]] after his original cue was lost after the [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]] earlier that year.<ref name=\"cue\">{{cite web|last1=Rawcliffe |first1=Jonathan | last2=Harlow| first2=Phil |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4467219.stm |title=Crucible Diary \u2013 Day Five |work=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2005 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> The original cue was eventually retrieved just before the World Championship but was found to be damaged and unusable. Having borrowed a friend's cue, he decided against practising, and went out drinking.<ref name=\"cue\" /> He played his first round match against Peter Ebdon hungover, and lost 2\u201310.<ref>{{cite web |last=Harlow |first=Phil |title=Gifted Hann guilty of wasting talent |work=BBC Sport |date=21 April 2005 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4470611.stm |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> Hann ended the season 22nd in the world rankings.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" />\n\n===Match-fixing allegations and resignation===\nThe day after his 2005 sex attack acquittal ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' alleged that Hann had agreed to lose his opening match against the 1997 world champion [[Ken Doherty]] at the China Open to one of its undercover reporters in return for \u00a350,000. The story had been held back so it would not prejudice the outcome of Hann's trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/sting-lands-hann-in-fixing-storm-20050511-gdlapv.html|title=Sting lands Hann in fixing storm|date=11 May 2005|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|agency=Australian Associated Press}}</ref> A hearing at the [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] (WPBSA) was convened after its panel was shown transcripts of video and audio footage of the meetings which took place between Hann and the undercover ''Sun'' journalists in March and April 2005.<ref name=\"ban\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4725612.stm|title=Guilty Hann given eight-year ban|date=17 February 2006|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> In September, he entered the [[2005 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] tournament,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A136353064/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=eead6db3|title=Hann to play on despite inquiry; Snooker|date=15 September 2005|work=The Times|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=84|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> before he withdrew one month later on medical grounds. Hann submitted a [[medical certificate]] and received a \u00a33,000 prize fund from the WPBSA.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Everton|first=Clive|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/oct/07/snooker.sport2|title=Snooker: Hann to miss Grand Prix as questions await|date=7 October 2005|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hann later failed to attend the first round of the [[2005 UK Championship|UK Championship]] for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4499386.stm|title=Hann misses UK Championship match|date=5 December 2005|work=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051215142955/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4499386.stm|archive-date=15 December 2005|access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HannDT\">{{Cite news|last=Dee|first=John|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/2369348/Hann-stages-second-no-show.html|title=Hann stages second no-show|date=6 December 2005|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706191837/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/2369348/Hann-stages-second-no-show.html|archive-date=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February 2006 he resigned from the WPBSA. Hann did not attend the hearing and was found guilty ''in absentia''. The newspaper did not go through with any agreement, but by agreeing to lose the game Hann was in breach of rule 2.8, which states \"a member shall not directly or indirectly solicit, attempt to solicit or accept any payment or any form of remuneration of benefit in exchange for influencing the outcome of any game of snooker or billiards.\"<ref name=\"ban\" /> Hann was banned from snooker until 2014 and also fined \u00a310,000.<ref name=\"ban\" /> He commented on the ban imposed on him in an interview with the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' in 2010, \"I was just the perfect scapegoat for them. I was a foreigner, I'd pretty much given up snooker and so I was fair game for them.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Banned Australian Quinten Hann slams John Higgins snooker match-fixing verdict|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/7990998/Banned-Australian-Quinten-Hann-slams-John-Higgins-snooker-match-fixing-verdict.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=9 September 2010|accessdate=27 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nIn October 2001, Hann invited an unidentified South African born woman to a hotel in London after midnight. Both had consumed alcohol at a bar at a club in the [[West End of London|West End]] and begun kissing. She allowed Hann to remove her lower clothing before he forced himself upon her. Police later arrested Hann and charged him with rape.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Driscoll|first=Margarette|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A89031888/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=8e9cdd15|title=Sure, I sleep around but I'm no rapist|date=14 July 2002|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=3|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He was instructed to surrender his travel documents and a Magistrates' Court judge allowed him to keep playing professional snooker as long as he told the police where he was residing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A79704893/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=0b686050|title=Aussie champ rape charge|date=30 October 2001|work=[[Herald Sun]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=002|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Hann appeared in [[Southwark Crown Court]] on 3 January 2002 and entered a plea of not guilty.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/snooker-player-denies-rape-charge-1-591803|title=Snooker player denies rape charge|date=4 January 2002|work=The Scotsman|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He was acquitted of the charges by a jury in July 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2083990.stm |title=Snooker player cleared of rape |work=BBC News |date=2 July 2002 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nHann was cleared of further sex attacks on two women in 2005. The women accused Hann of behaving like a \"crazed animal\" and said that they thought they were going to die. One of them claimed that he repeatedly struck her, an accusation that Hann strongly denied explaining that his mother had taught him to never raise a hand to a woman.<ref name=\"sex attack\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/4530169.stm |title=Snooker ace cleared of sex attack |work=BBC News |date=9 May 2005 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> Ultimately the case turned on the credibility of his accuser, which was undermined when it was admitted she had lied consistently under oath throughout the trial.<ref name=\"sex attack\" />\n\nIn October 2014, it was reported that the Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC) had started court proceedings at the Federal Court of Australia against Hann (now going under the name Quinten Hunter), general manager of broker Monarch FX (Monarch FX Group Pty Ltd). ASIC temporarily banned Monarch FX and Hann from offering financial services until November 2014 when the hearing resumes.<ref name=\"ASIC Ban\">{{cite web|url=http://forexmagnates.com/got-banned-australia-many-traders-lose-read-best-stories-week/ |title=Forex Magnates: \"ASIC Banned Monarch FX and Quinten Hunter\" |work=Forex Magnates |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> In 2016, Hann was banned from the financial services industry for four years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snookercentral.com/snooker-quinten-hann |title=Disgraced snooker player Quinten Hann cheats millions out of clients and given financial services ban from court |date=2016-07-24 |first=Robert |last=McGee |website=Snooker Central |access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[Snooker season 1995/1996|1995/<br/>96]]\n! [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/<br/>97]]\n! [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/<br/>98]]\n! [[Snooker season 1998/1999|1998/<br/>99]]\n! [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/<br/>00]]\n! [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/<br/>01]]\n! [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001/<br/>02]]\n! [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/<br/>03]]\n! [[Snooker season 2003/2004|2003/<br/>04]]\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/<br/>05]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|website=snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">From the 2010/2011 season it shows the ranking at the beginning of the season.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref group=\"nb\">New players on the Main Tour don't have a ranking.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 1996/1997|237]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 1997/1998|104]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 1998/1999|45]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 1999/2000|26]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2000/2001|32]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2001/2002|25]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2002/2003|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2003/2004|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2004/2005|18]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"30\" | '''Ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[World Open (snooker)|Grand Prix]]<ref group=\"nb\">The event also ran under the name LG Cup (2001/2002\u20132003/2004)</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1995 Grand Prix (snooker)|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1997 Grand Prix (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[1998 Grand Prix (snooker)|QF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| WD\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2000 Grand Prix (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2001 LG Cup (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2002 LG Cup (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2003 LG Cup (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2004 Grand Prix (snooker)|1R]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[British Open (snooker)|British Open]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1999 British Open (1998/1999)|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1999 British Open (1999/2000)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2000 British Open|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2001 British Open|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2002 British Open|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2003 British Open|3R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2004 British Open|2R]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1996 UK Championship|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1997 UK Championship|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1998 UK Championship|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| WD\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2000 UK Championship|QF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2001 UK Championship|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2002 UK Championship|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2003 UK Championship|QF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2004 UK Championship|2R]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Malta Cup]]<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"MAL\">The event also ran as the European Open (1995/1996\u20131996/1997 and 2001/2002\u20132003/2004) and Irish Open (1998/1999)</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| NH\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1998 Irish Open|1R]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Not Held\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2001 European Open (snooker)|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2003 European Open (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2004 European Open (snooker)|QF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| WD\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| [[Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| WD\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2001 Welsh Open (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2003 Welsh Open (snooker)|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2004 Welsh Open (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2005 Welsh Open (snooker)|2R]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]]<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"CHN\">The event ran under a different name as China International (1997/1998\u20131998/1999)</ref>\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Not Held\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| NR\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1999 China International|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2002 China Open (snooker)|2R]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Not Held\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2005 China Open (snooker)|1R]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[World Snooker Championship|World Championship]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| WD\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1998 World Snooker Championship|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2001 World Snooker Championship|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2002 World Snooker Championship|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2003 World Snooker Championship|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2004 World Snooker Championship|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2005 World Snooker Championship|1R]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"30\" | '''Non-ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Masters (snooker)|The Masters]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| A\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2003 Masters (snooker)|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2004 Masters (snooker)|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| A\n|-\n|colspan=\"30\" | '''Former ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Dubai Classic|Asian Classic]]<ref group=\"nb\">The event also ran under the name Thailand Classic (1995/1996)</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| colspan=\"30\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Tournament Not Held\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[German Masters|German Open]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1997 German Open (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| NR\n| colspan=\"30\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Tournament Not Held\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Thailand Masters]]<ref group=\"nb\" >The event also ran under the name Thailand Open (1995/1996\u20131996/1997)</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[1997 Thailand Open|QF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1999 Thailand Masters|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| WD\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2001 Thailand Masters|QF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2002 Thailand Masters|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| NR\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Not Held\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]]<ref group=\"nb\" >The event also ran under the names International Open (1995/1996\u20131996/1997) and Players Championship (2003/2004)</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1999 Scottish Open (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2000 Scottish Open (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2001 Scottish Open (snooker)|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2002 Scottish Open (snooker)|QF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2003 Scottish Open (snooker)|3R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2004 Players Championship (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| NH\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Irish Masters]]\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Non-Ranking Event\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2003 Irish Masters|QF]]\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2004 Irish Masters|SF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|NH / Not Held || event was not held.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|NR / Non-Ranking Event || event is/was no longer a ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|R / Ranking Event || event is/was a ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|MR / Minor-Ranking Event || event is/was a minor-ranking event.\n|}\n{{refbegin}}\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Career finals==\n===Amateur finals: 2 (1 title, 1 runner-up)===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n|width=\"80\"|'''Outcome'''\n|width=\"20\"|'''No.'''\n|width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n|width=\"250\"|'''Championship'''\n|width=\"200\"|'''Opponent in the final'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Score'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 1.\n| 1991\n| Australian Amateur Championship\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} David Collins\n| 4\u20135\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| 1994\n| [[IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship|IBSF World Under-21 Championship]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|David|Gray|dab=snooker player}}\n| 11\u201310<ref name=\":1\" />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hann, Quinten}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian snooker players]]\n[[Category:Australian pool players]]\n[[Category:World champions in pool]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Melbourne]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n|name = Quinten Hann\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|6|4}}\n|birth_place =[[Wagga Wagga]], [[New South Wales]]\n| Sport country= {{AUS}}\n| Nickname = The Wizard of Oz\n| Professional = 1995\u20132006\n| High ranking = 14 (2002\u20132004)\n| Century break = 41<ref name=\"centurybreaks\">{{cite web|title=Centuries|url=http://www.prosnookerblog.com/centuries/|website=Pro Snooker Blog|accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n| Prize money = [[Pound sterling|GB\u00a3]]432,600\n| High break = '''143''': <br> <small>1997 Grand Prix</small>\n| Best finish = Semi-final <small>([[Irish Masters (snooker)|2004 Irish Masters]])</small>\n| Ranking wins =\n| Other wins =\n}}\n'''Quinten Hann''' (born 4 June 1977) is an Australian former professional [[snooker]] player. He was the 1999 [[List of world eight-ball champions|WEPF World Eight-ball Champion]] and 1994 world under 21 champion. His highest break was a 143 that he made at the [[1997 Grand Prix (snooker)|1997 Grand Prix]] tournament. He was given an eight-year ban from snooker in February 2006 for match-fixing at the [[2005 China Open (snooker)|2005 China Open]], shortly before which he had resigned his membership of the [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] (WPBSA).\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and amateur career===\nBorn on 4 June 1977 in [[Wagga Wagga]], [[New South Wales]],<ref name=MRHoF/> Hann is the only child in a single parent family;<ref name=\"AgeApr98\" /> his father was absent from his life after they separated during the family's time in [[Melbourne]].<ref name=\"AgeApr98\" /><ref name=SMApr02>{{Cite news|last=Schlink|first=Leo|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85143514/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=04ceb7ac|title=Ex-Queensland boy shakes up snooker world \u2013 Loose cannon|date=28 April 2002|work=[[The Sunday Mail (Brisbane)|The Sunday Mail]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=026|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He was educated at the city's [[Samaritan Catholic College|Redden Catholic College]].<ref name=SMApr02/> Hann's mother Amanda purchased a [[Billiard table|snooker table]] for him to practise on when he turned nine.<ref name=\"AgeApr98\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/122858950/|title=Snooker's Melbourne demon|last=Hanlon|first=Peter|date=26 April 1998|work=[[The Age|The Sunday Age]]|access-date=30 September 2019|page=19|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He later took up [[Pool (cue sports)|pool]] at the age of ten after being introduced to it through a friend in [[Brisbane]].<ref name=\"SHFeb91\">{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A297577824/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=477e8786|title=At 13, Quinten Hann just wants to pot gold|date=3 February 1991|work=The Sun-Herald|access-date=15 March 2019|page=81|url-access=subscription |via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref> Hann played pool during the weekends, until his mother swayed him away from playing it in [[Pub|public houses]]. She telephoned a snooker coach to teach her son the game.<ref name=\"MNApr98\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.messengernewspapers.co.uk/news/7234980.YOUNG_snooker_star_Quinten_Hann_is_hoping_to_follow_the_yellow_brick_road_all_the_way_to_the_top_/|title=Young snooker star Quinten Hann is hoping to follow the yellow brick road all the way to the top|date=9 April 1998|work=Sale & Altrincham Messenger|access-date=15 March 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930175954/https://www.messengernewspapers.co.uk/news/7234980.young-snooker-star-quinten-hann-is-hoping-to-follow-the-yellow-brick-road-all-the-way-to-the-top/|archive-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nAt age 12, Hann became the youngest qualifier for the [[Australian Goldfields Open]] in June 1989, losing in the last 16 stage to the under-21 national champion [[Steve Mifsud]]. Although he broke his left wrist in a motorcycle accident, which caused him to play in a plaster, he won the Victoria Under-12 Championship in March 1990. Three months later, Hann finished runner-up in his group at the 1990 [[IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship]], with six victories from eight matches.<ref name=\"SHFeb91\" /> Hann's mother sold the family home and car and possessions to finance her son's career and moved them from Wagga Wagga to England in late 1989.<ref name=SHFeb91/><ref name=GuardianJan91>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A171221043/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=d600ab9a|title=Snooker: Hann's TV spectacular|last=Everton|first=Clive|date=21 January 1991|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2019|page=13|url-access=subscription |via=General OneFile}}</ref> She had written to [[Matchroom Sport]] founder [[Barry Hearn]], who offered his services to Hann.<ref name=SHFeb91/>  \n\nAt the age of 13, Hann produced a break of 100 at the [[1991 World Masters]] under-16 tournament, making him the youngest player to compile a televised [[century break]].<ref name=\"GuardianJan91\" /> He reached the final of the Australian Amateur Championship at age 14 and he then took part in the [[IBSF World Snooker Championship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A170911444/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=8e326611|title=Sport: Sixth Column|date=29 May 1993|work=The Guardian|access-date=16 March 2019|page=19|url-access=subscription |via=General OneFile}}</ref> On 13 October 1991, Hann was given a suspended ban by the Australian Billiards and Snooker Council from all domestic and overseas competitions for spitting on a competitor's mother. This was invoked after the New South Wales country junior championship in January 1993 when he swore at the referee following a decision that favoured his opponent and entered the Lithgow Workmen's Club licensed poker-machine area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/120521943/|title=Bad boy of snooker is grounded|date=14 March 1993|work=Sunday Age|access-date=16 March 2019|page=24|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The ban was appealed by Hann's family to the [[High Court of Australia]]; it was reduced to one year.<ref name=TimesApr98>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A59979532/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=1fcc2b2f|title=1998 Embassy World Championship; Snooker|last=Yates|first=Phil|date=18 April 1998|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=1 October 2019|page=35|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In the meantime, he won the 1992 Australian Open 8-ball Championship, defeating Lou Condo 6\u20131 in the final and later beat [[David Gray (snooker player)|David Gray]] 11\u201310 to win the 1994 IBSF World Under-21 Championship.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A103932605/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=191e1031|title=Hann's shot at the big time / Inside Back|last=Kershler|first=Ray|date=4 April 1998|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 March 2019|page=151|url-access=subscription |via=Infotrac Newsstand}}</ref>\n\n===Professional career===\nHann became a professional player in 1995.<ref name=MRHoF>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museumriverina.com.au/collections/hall-of-fame/inductees/hann,-quinte|title=Quinten Hann|work=Museum of the Riverina|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324000147/http://www.museumriverina.com.au/collections/hall-of-fame/inductees/hann,-quinte|archive-date=24 March 2017|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> In five months of his first season, he reached {{Abbr|No.|World ranking nunber}} 237 in the world by competing in satellite tournaments.<ref name=\"DTMar98\" /> Not discouraged by this, he met Brandon Parker through another player; Parker agreed to manage Hann's career.<ref name=\"MNApr98\" /> Hann was now able to enter tournaments abroad in the [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/1997 season]], reaching the quarter-finals of the [[1997 Thailand Open]], and rising to No. 104 in the world.<ref name=\"DTMar98\">{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A103934862/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=7db4d773|title=Hann is snooker's new man|last=Kershler|first=Ray|date=27 March 1998|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=1 October 2019|page=115|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 1996, he was paired with [[Robby Foldvari]] and [[Stan Gorski]] to represent Australia at the [[1996 World Cup (snooker)|Snooker World Cup]]. The trio lasted until the quarter-finals, being defeated 5\u201310 by England.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/260444462/|title=Bond broken by Australian welder|last=Everton|first=Clive|date=7 November 1996|work=The Guardian|access-date=30 September 2019|page=24|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> \n\nFor the [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/1998 season]], Hann reached the televised stages of more tournaments, lasting until the second-rounds of the [[1997 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] (where he set a record of 13 consecutive victories with a 5\u20134 margin and compiled the highest break of his career, a 143),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/9798/gp97_res.shtml|title=Grand Prix 1997|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12287044.higgins-is-handed-win-hann-blows-his-act-by-showboating/|title=Higgins is handed win Hann blows his act by showboating|date=21 October 1997|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|access-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001131511/https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12287044.higgins-is-handed-win-hann-blows-his-act-by-showboating/|archive-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> the [[1997 UK Championship|UK Championship]],<ref name=\"TimesApr98\" /> and the [[1997 German Open (snooker)|German Open]] tournaments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/9798/go97_res.shtml|title=German Open 1997|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> He lost in the first round of the preliminary stages of the [[1998 British Open|British Open]] with a 5\u20130 [[Whitewash (sport)|whitewash]] to [[Drew Henry]] in April 1998.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-hann-suffers-heaviest-defeat-of-season-1154189.html|title=Snooker: Hann suffers heaviest defeat of season|date=3 April 1998|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> One month earlier, Hann became the first Australian player since [[Eddie Charlton]] in 1992 to qualify for the [[1998 World Snooker Championship|World Snooker Championship]].<ref name=\"TimesApr98\" /> He was eliminated by [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 9\u201310 in the first round,<ref name=\"AgeApr98\" /> ending the season ranked No. 45 in the world.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" />\n\nHann won the Lindrum Masters multi-format tournament in [[Newcastle, New South Wales]] in September 1998. After the tournament, he met with his mother and World Snooker chairman [[Rex Williams]], and agreed to change his lifestyle and public image.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A103859017/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=674ff5c2|title=Bad boy is shaping up / Inside Back|last=Kershler|first=Ray|date=7 November 1998|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=30 September 2019|page=159|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Hann advanced to the quarter-finals of the [[1998 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] tournament in the following month,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A91704804/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=f9dfa5e8|title=Snooker|date=21 October 1998|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|access-date=1 October 2019|page=110|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> losing to [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] in a 5\u20130 whitewash.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-lee-is-far-too-hot-for-hann-1180084.html|title=Snooker: Lee is far too hot for Hann|date=23 October 1998|work=The Independent|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> He lost 5\u20139 to Marcus Campbell in the second round of the [[1998 UK Championship|UK Championship]] in November; Hann's opponent criticised him for conceding two [[Glossary_of_cue_sports_terms#frame|frames]] in the match.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A82949160/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=634d0216|title=Campbell gets the breaks as Hann makes a spectacle|last=Baxter|first=Trevor|date=23 November 1998|work=[[The Scotsman]]|access-date=1 October 2019|page=32|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Hann replicated this performance once more during the season, this time in the [[1999 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] in February 1999, losing 2\u20135 to [[Graeme Dott]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-hanns-theatrics-earn-a-rebuke-1071638.html|title=Snooker: Hann's theatrics earn a rebuke|date=18 February 1999|work=The Independent|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> He concluded the season ranked No. 26 in the world.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> \n\nBefore the start of the [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/2000 snooker season]], Hann won the [[WEPF World Eight-ball championship|WEPF World 8-Ball Pool Championship]] to become the only player born outside the United Kingdom and Ireland to claim the title,<ref>{{Cite journal|date=October 2013|title=How the World Began|url=https://issuu.com/bud144/docs/magazine_ed_6_v3_layout_1|journal=World Pool Magazine|edition=6|pages=21|access-date=1 October 2019|via=[[Issuu]]}}</ref> and defeated [[Oliver Ortmann]] to successfully defend the Lindrum Masters tournament in August.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.snookerimages.co.uk/news.html|title=Hann triumphs again|last=Dee|first=John|date=13 August 1999|access-date=1 October 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19991008212759/http://www.snookerimages.co.uk/news.html|archive-date=8 October 1999|website=Snooker Images}}</ref> He qualified for the [[1999 British Open (1999/2000)|British Open]] in September, lasting until the second round when he was defeated 2\u20135 by Stephen Lee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/9900/bo99_res.shtml|title=British Open 1999 (autumn)|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> In October Hann withdrew from the [[1999 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] due to his father suffering a myocardial infarction,<ref name=IndyNov99>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-hanns-year-ends-early-1126525.html|title=Snooker: Hann's year ends early|date=16 November 1999|work=The Independent|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> and then the Australian Nine-Ball Championship to pursue riding motorcycles as a hobby.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85449031/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=f3de8b33|title=Nine-Ball Showdown|last=Clancy|first=Brett|date=29 October 1999|work=The Advertiser|access-date=1 October 2019|page=093|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> While doing this, he sustained a [[clavicle fracture]] and a bruised wrist in an accident in Melbourne,<ref name=IndyNov99/><ref name=GuardianOct00>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/story/0,3604,376486,00.html|title=Hann takes his cue from Australia's golden haul|last=Everton|first=Clive|date=3 October 2000|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001142527/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/story/0,3604,376486,00.html|archive-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> requiring him to not partake in the next six tournaments as he recovered from the injuries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2006/0215/201395-hann/|title=Hann quits snooker|date=15 February 2006|access-date=1 October 2019|work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]}}</ref> Hann returned to competition at the [[2000 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] in March 2000, reaching the second-round where he lost 4\u20135 to eventual champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A61404483/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=042ec2ea|title=Maximum impact by O'Sullivan; Snooker|date=6 April 2000|work=The Times|access-date=1 October 2019|page=31|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> \n\nHe began the [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/2001 season]] ranked world No. 32.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> Hann prepared for the upcoming campaign by increasing his practise at his home in Melbourne.<ref name=GuardianOct00/> Before that Hann lasted until the semi-final stage of the World 8-Ball Championship in June 2000.<ref name=110Profile>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/php/SnookerProfiles/viewsnook.php?p_id=28|title=Quinten Hann: At A Glance|website=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040218101150/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/php/SnookerProfiles/viewsnook.php?p_id=28|archive-date=18 February 2004|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann was eliminated from the second round at the Grand Prix tournament,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yates|first=Phil|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A66225251/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=76f29654|title=Angry Hann sees red; Snooker|date=19 October 2000|work=The Times|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=37|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and was booed by spectators for smashing the [[Billiard ball|cue ball]] into the pack of {{Cuegloss|red ball|reds}} in the final three frames of his match against O'Sullivan.<ref name=SMHApr02>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/australian-hope-nears-meltdown-at-the-crucible-20020425-gdf83u.html|title=Australian hope nears meltdown at The Crucible|date=25 April 2002|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He earned an official reprimand of \u00a3750 for \"unprofessional behaviour\" for nonperformance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/413.htm|title=Aussie Hann Loses Some Of His Grand Prix Prize Money|last=Dee|first=John|date=8 January 2001|work=Embassy Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010429054525/http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/413.htm|archive-date=29 April 2001|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann broke a bone in his foot in a [[parachuting|parachute jump]] before the [[2000 UK Championship]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nelson|first=Kevin|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A67368922/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=434f9e7d|title=Snooker: Pain and gain for hobbling Hann|date=28 November 2000|work=The Independent|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=27|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and was required to play shoeless in a tournament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/in_depth/2000/uk_championship_snooker/1036217.stm|title=High, wide and Hann-some|last=Everton|first=Clive|date=22 November 2000|work=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> where he lasted until the quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Everton|first=Clive|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A75684685/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=82e067a4|title=Snooker: O'Sullivan plays safe to leave Hann in awe|date=1 December 2000|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=36|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He also reached the quarter-finals of the [[2001 Thailand Masters|Thailand Masters]] before losing to [[John Parrott]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0001/tm2001_res.shtml|title=Blue Eagle/Thai Airways Thailand Masters 2001|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann qualified for the [[2001 World Snooker Championship]] and was drawn against world number 16 [[Dave Harold]] in the first round.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kershler|first=Ray|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A103584316/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=41a151fb|title=Hann no fall guy this time|date=29 March 2001|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=044|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The match saw Hann lose 5\u201310 to Harold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/in_depth/2001/world_snooker_championship/1291048.stm|title=Harold outguns Aussie Hann|date=22 April 2001|work=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021106173039/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/in_depth/2001/world_snooker_championship/1291048.stm|archive-date=6 November 2002|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe commenced the [[2001\u201302 snooker season|2001/2002 season]] as the world number 25.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> Hann reached the second round of the season's first three ranking tournaments,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/581.htm|title=Alan McManus Outpots Aussie Quinten Hann|last=Dee|first=John|date=3 October 2001|work=Embassy Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011005014226/http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/581.htm|archive-date=5 October 2001|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Yates|first=Phil|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A79216641/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=86ac9d60|title=Williams silences Hann with limp effort; Snooker|date=17 October 2001|work=The Times|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=8|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na04789.php|title=\"Grateful\" Doherty Flattens Hann|last=Hendon|first=David|date=25 November 2001|website=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011201064933/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na04789.php|archive-date=1 December 2001|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> before improving his performance to last until the third round of the [[2002 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] and the [[2002 Thailand Masters|Thailand Masters]].<ref name=110Profile/> By progressing beyond the third round of the [[2002 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] later in 2002, he ensured that he would end the season as one of the world's top sixteen ranked players, the first time this had happened for an Australian player since [[Eddie Charlton]] in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dee|first=John|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/3025707/Snooker-Hann-breaks-into-top-16.html|title=Snooker: Hann breaks into top 16|date=10 April 2002|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hann ended the tournament in the quarter-final stage and critiqued the World Snooker Association's running of snooker.<ref name=110Profile/> He concluded the season in the second round of the World Snooker Championship with a victory over [[Paul Hunter (snooker player)|Paul Hunter]] in the first round and a loss to Stephen Lee in the next stage.<ref name=110Profile/> Players and pundits criticised Hann for breaking up the red balls in a pool-style method during both of his matches and for unprofessional-ism in the second game.<ref name=SMHApr02/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/extrovert-aussie-knocked-out-in-second-round-20020501-gdf8n7.html|title=Extrovert Aussie knocked out in second round|date=1 May 2002|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Australian Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2002\u201303 snooker season|2002/2003 season]] saw Hann begin as a player who was ranked 14th in the world.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> He was unable to win a match in the season's first four ranking tournaments.<ref name=\"MRHoF\" /> Hann's top sixteen world ranking allowed him to enter the non-ranking [[2003 Masters (snooker)|Masters tournament]] for the first time in his professional career,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burnside|first=Brian|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A88452030/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=725fdad5|title=Snooker: Hann awaits return to top-level competition|date=6 July 2002|work=The Independent|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=9|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> losing in the first round 4\u20136 to Lee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0203/bm2003_res.shtml|title=Benson & Hedges Masters 2003|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> This marked a turning point in his season as he reached the second round of the next two competitions and the quarter-finals of the [[2003 Irish Masters]].<ref name=\"MRHoF\" /> At the [[2003 World Snooker Championship|World Snooker Championship]], Hann defeated Parrott 10\u20135 in the first round,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/957.htm|title=Hann Takes Care Of Parrott's Challenge|last=Dee|first=John|date=20 April 2003|work=Embassy Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030608115619/http://www.embassysnooker.com/news/957.htm|archive-date=8 June 2003|access-date=21 February 2003}}</ref> before he was defeated by Mark Williams 13\u20132 in the second round.<ref>{{cite news|last=Warren|first=Dan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/2980353.stm|title=Williams powers past Hann|date=28 April 2003|accessdate=19 March 2011|url-status=live|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nHe retained his ranking of 14th in the world for the [[2003\u201304 snooker season|2003/2004 season]].<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> Hann moved to Ealing after the 2003 world championship and began practising regularly at Ealing Snooker Club in a bid to establish himself as one of the world's top 16 players.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mistry|first=Ushma|url=https://www.ealingtimes.co.uk/sport/454639.hann-ealing-move-could-save-my-game/|title=Hann: Ealing move could save my game|date=29 January 2004|work=Ealing Times|access-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He got through to the quarter-finals of the [[2003 UK Championship|UK Championship]] for the first time, where he played Ronnie O'Sullivan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/snooker-practice-makes-perfect-hann-1670109|title=Snooker: Practice makes perfect for Hann|date=25 November 2003|work=[[Evening Chronicle]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He lost the match 3\u20139.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A110830104/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=6a5b6e56|title=Hann crushed by O'Sullivan|date=29 November 2003|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=095|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> At the [[2004 Masters (snooker)|2004 Masters]], Hann was defeated in the first round 3\u20136 by [[Peter Ebdon]].<ref name=\"BBCEbdonHann\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/3460173.stm|title=Ebdon eases past Hann|date=4 February 2004|access-date=9 February 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212012442/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/3460173.stm|archive-date=12 February 2019|work=BBC Sport|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He later progressed to the quarter-finals of the [[2004 European Open (snooker)|European Open]] in Malta and lost to local player [[Tony Drago]] 1\u20135.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0304/eo2004_res.shtml|title=European Open 2004|website=snooker.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann progressed into the first ranking semi-final of his professional career at the [[2004 Irish Masters|Irish Masters]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dee|first=John|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A114660218/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=ebc73e32|title=Hann in last four|date=27 March 2004|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> This made him the first Australian player to reach the semi-finals of a tournament since [[Warren King (snooker player)|Warren King]] at the [[1990 Classic (snooker)|1990 Classic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/snooker/hann-reaches-masters-final-140120.html|title=Hann reaches Masters final|date=26 March 2004|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hann conceded a frame while 30\u201324 ahead and executed a pool-style break off in his 5\u20136 defeat to Ebdon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/3575755.stm|title=Ebdon edges out Hann|date=28 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nHis final match of the season was a 4\u201310 defeat to [[Andy Hicks]] in the first round of the [[2004 World Snooker Championship|World Snooker Championship]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Yates|first=Phil|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A115536038/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=1fe35ca1|title=Defeated Hann displays his ugly side again; Snooker|date=19 April 2004|work=The Times|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=36|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> After the match referee Lawrie Annandale separated the two players from having a physical alteration after Hann made a threatening comment to Hicks when the latter suggested he would lose his top 16 world ranking.<ref name=\":0\" /> He challenged Hicks to a fight; In the event fellow snooker player [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]] stood in for Hicks at a charity boxing match with Hann which the latter won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/funny_old_game/3797515.stm |title=Hann triumphs in Pot Whack |work=BBC Sport |date=12 June 2004 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> Hann also fought [[Dublin GAA]] player, [[Johnny Magee]], in a charity boxing match in Dublin in September 2004 after He suggested that [[Gaelic football]]ers were not as robust as Australia [[Australian rules football|rules footballers]]. He had his nose broken, with Magee winning in three rounds.<ref name=\"accidents\">{{cite web|url=http://www.breakingnews.ie/2006/02/14/story244688.html|title=Hann's controversial career seems over|date=14 February 2006|website=BreakingNews.ie|publisher=[[Thomas Crosbie Holdings]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311033533/http://www.breakingnews.ie/2006/02/14/story244688.html|archivedate=11 March 2007|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bunce |first=Jane |title=Hann lost for cash \u2013 report |date=11 May 2005 |website= theage.com.au |publisher=[[The Age|The Age Company]] |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Sport/Hann-lost-for-cash--report/2005/05/10/1115584957599.html |accessdate=22 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nHann fell to 18th in the world rankings before the commencement of the [[2004\u201305 snooker season|2004/2005 season]].<ref name=\"Ranking history\" /> He reached the quarter finals of the 2004 World 8-Ball Championship and lost 6\u20139 to [[Darren Appleton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kozoom.com/en/pool-billiard/players/hann-quinten/matches.html|title=Player US Pool: Quinten Hann|website=Kozoom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Hann withdrew from the [[2005 Malta Cup]] because he had a fractured finger.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.smh.com.au/sport/haan-pulls-out-of-malta-cup-20050203-gdkmay.html|title=Haan pulls out of Malta Cup|date=3 February 2005|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|agency=Press Assocation}}</ref> The [[2005 World Snooker Championship|2005 World Championship]] saw Hann forced to play with a new [[Cue stick|cue]] after his original cue was lost after the [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]] earlier that year.<ref name=\"cue\">{{cite web|last1=Rawcliffe |first1=Jonathan | last2=Harlow| first2=Phil |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4467219.stm |title=Crucible Diary \u2013 Day Five |work=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2005 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> The original cue was eventually retrieved just before the World Championship but was found to be damaged and unusable. Having borrowed a friend's cue, he decided against practising, and went out drinking.<ref name=\"cue\" /> He played his first round match against Peter Ebdon hungover, and lost 2\u201310.<ref>{{cite web |last=Harlow |first=Phil |title=Gifted Hann guilty of wasting talent |work=BBC Sport |date=21 April 2005 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4470611.stm |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> Hann ended the season 22nd in the world rankings.<ref name=\"Ranking history\" />\n\n===Match-fixing allegations and resignation===\nThe day after his 2005 sex attack acquittal ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' alleged that Hann had agreed to lose his opening match against the 1997 world champion [[Ken Doherty]] at the China Open to one of its undercover reporters in return for \u00a350,000. The story had been held back so it would not prejudice the outcome of Hann's trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/sting-lands-hann-in-fixing-storm-20050511-gdlapv.html|title=Sting lands Hann in fixing storm|date=11 May 2005|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|agency=Australian Associated Press}}</ref> A hearing at the [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] (WPBSA) was convened after its panel was shown transcripts of video and audio footage of the meetings which took place between Hann and the undercover ''Sun'' journalists in March and April 2005.<ref name=\"ban\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4725612.stm|title=Guilty Hann given eight-year ban|date=17 February 2006|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> In September, he entered the [[2005 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] tournament,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A136353064/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=eead6db3|title=Hann to play on despite inquiry; Snooker|date=15 September 2005|work=The Times|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=84|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> before he withdrew one month later on medical grounds. Hann submitted a [[medical certificate]] and received a \u00a33,000 prize fund from the WPBSA.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Everton|first=Clive|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/oct/07/snooker.sport2|title=Snooker: Hann to miss Grand Prix as questions await|date=7 October 2005|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hann later failed to attend the first round of the [[2005 UK Championship|UK Championship]] for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4499386.stm|title=Hann misses UK Championship match|date=5 December 2005|work=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051215142955/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4499386.stm|archive-date=15 December 2005|access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HannDT\">{{Cite news|last=Dee|first=John|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/2369348/Hann-stages-second-no-show.html|title=Hann stages second no-show|date=6 December 2005|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706191837/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/2369348/Hann-stages-second-no-show.html|archive-date=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February 2006 he resigned from the WPBSA. Hann did not attend the hearing and was found guilty ''in absentia''. The newspaper did not go through with any agreement, but by agreeing to lose the game Hann was in breach of rule 2.8, which states \"a member shall not directly or indirectly solicit, attempt to solicit or accept any payment or any form of remuneration of benefit in exchange for influencing the outcome of any game of snooker or billiards.\"<ref name=\"ban\" /> Hann was banned from snooker until 2014 and also fined \u00a310,000.<ref name=\"ban\" /> He commented on the ban imposed on him in an interview with the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' in 2010, \"I was just the perfect scapegoat for them. I was a foreigner, I'd pretty much given up snooker and so I was fair game for them.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Banned Australian Quinten Hann slams John Higgins snooker match-fixing verdict|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/7990998/Banned-Australian-Quinten-Hann-slams-John-Higgins-snooker-match-fixing-verdict.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=9 September 2010|accessdate=27 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nIn October 2001, Hann invited an unidentified South African born woman to a hotel in London after midnight. Both had consumed alcohol at a bar at a club in the [[West End of London|West End]] and begun kissing. She allowed Hann to remove her lower clothing before he forced himself upon her. Police later arrested Hann and charged him with rape.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Driscoll|first=Margarette|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A89031888/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=8e9cdd15|title=Sure, I sleep around but I'm no rapist|date=14 July 2002|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=3|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He was instructed to surrender his travel documents and a Magistrates' Court judge allowed him to keep playing professional snooker as long as he told the police where he was residing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A79704893/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=0b686050|title=Aussie champ rape charge|date=30 October 2001|work=[[Herald Sun]]|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live|page=002|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Hann appeared in [[Southwark Crown Court]] on 3 January 2002 and entered a plea of not guilty.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/snooker-player-denies-rape-charge-1-591803|title=Snooker player denies rape charge|date=4 January 2002|work=The Scotsman|access-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He was acquitted of the charges by a jury in July 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2083990.stm |title=Snooker player cleared of rape |work=BBC News |date=2 July 2002 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nHann was cleared of further sex attacks on two women in 2005. The women accused Hann of behaving like a \"crazed animal\" and said that they thought they were going to die. One of them claimed that he repeatedly struck her, an accusation that Hann strongly denied explaining that his mother had taught him to never raise a hand to a woman.<ref name=\"sex attack\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/4530169.stm |title=Snooker ace cleared of sex attack |work=BBC News |date=9 May 2005 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> Ultimately the case turned on the credibility of his accuser, which was undermined when it was admitted she had lied consistently under oath throughout the trial.<ref name=\"sex attack\" />\n\nIn October 2014, it was reported that the Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC) had started court proceedings at the Federal Court of Australia against Hann (now going under the name Quinten Hunter), general manager of broker Monarch FX (Monarch FX Group Pty Ltd). ASIC temporarily banned Monarch FX and Hann from offering financial services until November 2014 when the hearing resumes.<ref name=\"ASIC Ban\">{{cite web|url=http://forexmagnates.com/got-banned-australia-many-traders-lose-read-best-stories-week/ |title=Forex Magnates: \"ASIC Banned Monarch FX and Quinten Hunter\" |work=Forex Magnates |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> In 2016, Hann was banned from the financial services industry for four years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snookercentral.com/snooker-quinten-hann |title=Disgraced snooker player Quinten Hann cheats millions out of clients and given financial services ban from court |date=2016-07-24 |first=Robert |last=McGee |website=Snooker Central |access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[Snooker season 1995/1996|1995/<br/>96]]\n! [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/<br/>97]]\n! [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/<br/>98]]\n! [[Snooker season 1998/1999|1998/<br/>99]]\n! [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/<br/>00]]\n! [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/<br/>01]]\n! [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001/<br/>02]]\n! [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/<br/>03]]\n! [[Snooker season 2003/2004|2003/<br/>04]]\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/<br/>05]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|website=snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">From the 2010/2011 season it shows the ranking at the beginning of the season.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref group=\"nb\">New players on the Main Tour don't have a ranking.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 1996/1997|237]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 1997/1998|104]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 1998/1999|45]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 1999/2000|26]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2000/2001|32]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2001/2002|25]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2002/2003|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2003/2004|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2004/2005|18]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"30\" | '''Ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[World Open (snooker)|Grand Prix]]<ref group=\"nb\">The event also ran under the name LG Cup (2001/2002\u20132003/2004)</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1995 Grand Prix (snooker)|1R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1997 Grand Prix (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[1998 Grand Prix (snooker)|QF]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| WD\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2000 Grand Prix (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2001 LG Cup (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2002 LG Cup (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2003 LG Cup (snooker)|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2004 Grand Prix (snooker)|1R]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[British Open (snooker)|British Open]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| LQ\n| style=\"text-align:cent